    <item>
      <title>Leopardi, Trap, and the Bias of Conscious Music</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/passions/madamewild/</link>
      <pubDate>Sat, 22 Nov 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/passions/madamewild/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;There is a widespread prejudice, almost a knee-jerk reaction, that plagues modern music. A sharp line is drawn by purists: on one side, &amp;ldquo;Conscious Rap,&amp;rdquo; seen as noble and socially useful; on the other, the new urban wave, often labeled as superficial, guilty of not addressing the &amp;ldquo;great themes.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Yet, looking beyond the surface and the labels, this dichotomy has roots far deeper than music. It is not a question of beats or autotune; it is the same philosophical crossroads once traversed by Giacomo Leopardi.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
